<font color="#FF0000">ASK YOURSELF WHY</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct 22 10:30:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I went to war the first time because I perceived a threat to America.  I knew that the war was real before I graduated from flight school.  Upper classmen who had harrassed the crap out of me began to show up on the KIA list that we kept on our bulletin board.  For some reason I forgave them of the many pushups and snide remarks.  Above all I began to contemplate Why so many of them were dying.  Class rosters began to get pretty thin.  I never thought of not going.. but began to wonder if I would make it.  The death of these men just made America more precious to me.<br><br>
Somewhat calloused, I went on my second tour to help keep Americans from dying.  I could never advocate that a man throw his values to the ground simply because he was fearful.  I would not and will not fail to address issues because of a selfish need to keep my butt out of hot water!<br><br>
When I came home from my first tour I was thrilled to get on the freedom plane and head home.  I was amazed that I had made it and reflected back on the many who had not.  I began to feel guilt.<br><br>
I left Vietnam on my second tour loaded in a stretcher, told that I would never walk again.  I felt no guilt..knowing that I was no longer useful to my friends who were still in the fray.<br><br>
I have little or no tolerance for those who proclaim that political reasons kept them from going.  I honor those who did not want to go because of spiritual/religious reasons, something ingrained long before the war arrived.<br><br>
I do not go out of my way to criticize those who didn't go (whatever reasons) but I will go out of my way to address a bunch of cowardly bastards who take it upon themselves to find fault with me for accepting the challange.<br><br>
My greatest respect goes to guys like Tom Dier.  More mature young men who did not want to go.. but went anyway!<br><br>
The war is over, physically... emotionally and mentally it goes on in my head and always will.  I don't need blatant cowards blasting me with their self righteous bullshit to ease their wounds of shame.  Every man had a right to choose.. let each live with what they chose to do.  Me.. I have no regrets for going.  I do regret the loss of life and human suffering... and the piss poor way that things were conducted.<br><br>
Don't like to ask others why they went or didn't... I'm too busy asking myself!  When I weigh the merits of living in the United States of America as opposed to living in a communist country, when I think on the sacrifices made before my time, when I hear the National Anthem played, when I look at children playing...I find my answer.<br><br>
Whenever &quot;Freedom&quot; throws a party, I attend with an invitation... I don't have to feel that I have crashed the party as a mooch or freeloader!<br><br>
Mustang Two Four
